Kai Ferragallo-Hawkins
The World Bank (and more prominently, the IMF) are very free market, and tend to give out loans to developing countries on the condition that they reform their country to implement these policies

yet those policies then can allow foreign entities to get the counties wealth in the name of “development”, or fail to account for local conditions and end up hurting the economy. Those loans can also fall into less then reputable hands whose corruption then forces the country to have to deal with repaying the loan in the future

Some of those free market ideas show in that intervention. The idea that all you need is vocational training and to teach poor people how to save can to often put the blame for poverty onto the poor, and the idea that they simply cannot save for their health conditions or can’t get a job to get themselves out. But often, there are no reputable jobs, no safe levels of infrastructure, and little confrontation of what causes environmental health issues

There's definetely similarities with me. I know that academics has been important for my self-image (look at me in high school getting perfect attendance :0). I got built up and left wanting the impression of myself as being intelligent & capable, and I do get unsatisifed if I feel like that's not the case. But I've steadied myself a lot more these days then I did before - I've noticed that I can mess up in a class or a grade and be fine with it, even if I do very much want that grade. I think at some point I realized that what I really wanted out of academics was not being recognized, but just knowing and creating more. And it really feels like the perception that I want for myself comes around when I simply do what I want to do, rather than chasing after that perception, because it becomes easier to not get stuck up in the negativity that will always exist and to take that to heart. Similar thing with social interactions for me - it became a lot easier when I understood that what I periceved as recognition for my efforts was less important to me than simply being a positive point now and for the future.
Oct 22, 2023, 2:49 PM
Kai Ferragallo-Hawkins
The funny thing with that too - we, as people, are really bad at understanding the enormity of time. There's a situation within literature where people write 5 years as having monumental changes, while in 1000 years the world has barely changed, because once the number gets so big we begin to simpify it. Yet, in reality, it is that 5 years done again and again.

Where I'm going with that is that there is a lot of history packed into one day, one week, one month, one year. The amount that can change, that we can do, is incredible. Yet, at the same time, what we do, it's recognition and it's effects, will eventually pass. In life, we are already beating the enormous odds by even being here, by being able to think and feel, and it is the moments and the moments that come afterwards that matter. It's a lot, but also something that means that, at the end of the day, we get to choose what matters, and what is important to ourselves. The most random, miniscule things and moments are just as meaningful as the achievements. The interesting thing about satisfacion is that everything can be satisfying and everything can be unsatisfying, and success is entirely self-defined. The most "successful" people in the world seem to be so caught up in the fact that they don't have more that they are never satisfied (hi, Elon).
